\begin_layout Proof
Since all 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 points need to be on the plane then 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax+By+Cz+D=0$
\end_inset

 must apply to these 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We know that the two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2-0,0-0,2-1\right)=\left(2,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(6-0,2-0,3-1\right)=\left(6,2,2\right)$
\end_inset

 are parallel to the plane so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,0,1\right)\times\left(6,2,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is a normal to the plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Meaning that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\begin{matrix}i & j & k\\
2 & 0 & 1\\
6 & 2 & 2
\end{matrix}\right|=-2\hat{i}-\left(4-6\right)\hat{j}+\left(4-0\right)\hat{k}=-2\hi+2\hj+4\hk$
\end_inset

 is a normal to the plane.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $A=-2,B=2,C=4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 is on the plane then 
\begin_inset Formula $-2\cdot0+2\cdot0+4\cdot1+D=0\Ra D=-4$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So the plane is 
\begin_inset Formula $-2x+2y+4z-4=0$
\end_inset

 is the (only) plane that contains the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let's assign 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right),y\left(t\right),z\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-2\left(t^{2}+t\right)+2\left(t^{2}-t\right)+4\left(t+1\right)-4=\cancel{-2t^{2}}\cancel{-2t}+\cancel{2t^{2}}\cancel{-2t}+\cancel{4t}+4-4=4-4=0=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So we got that the plane's equation is true for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x\left(t\right),y\left(t\right),z\left(t\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 So the entire curve is on the plane.
\end_layout

