\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
From previous section, we get that only the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 affects the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 So for each value of value 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, all the vectors with an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{k}{\left|\vec{v}\right|}\right)$
\end_inset

 get the same value with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So let's cross product a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}=\left(a,b,c\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(a,b,c\right)\times\left(0,0,1\right)=\left|\begin{matrix}\hi & \hj & \hk\\
a & b & c\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{matrix}\right|=\left(b-0\right)\hi-\left(a-0\right)\hj+\left(0-0\right)\hk=b\hi-a\hj+0\hk
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
And the magnitude of the cross product is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{b^{2}+a^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(a,b,c\right)=\frac{\sqrt{b^{2}+a^{2}}}{\left|\left(a,b,c\right)\right|}=\frac{\sqrt{b^{2}+a^{2}}}{\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}}=k\Ra\sqrt{b^{2}+a^{2}}=k\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}=b^{2}+a^{2}=k^{2}\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)\Ra
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Ra b^{2}+a^{2}=k^{2}a^{2}+k^{2}b^{2}+k^{2}c^{2}\Ra\left(k^{2}-1\right)a^{2}+\left(k^{2}-1\right)b^{2}+k^{2}c^{2}=0\Ra
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Ra\left(k^{2}-1\right)a^{2}+\left(k^{2}-1\right)b^{2}+k^{2}c^{2}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0$
\end_inset

 there is no solution because the fraction of two square root will never
 be negative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+b^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 but in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 this is possible only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=0$
\end_inset

.
 And 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 can be anything.
 So all the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,c\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $1>k>0$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k^{2}-1\right)<0$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(k^{2}-1\right)=\left(1-k^{2}\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a^{2}}{\frac{k^{2}}{\left(1-k^{2}\right)}}+\frac{b^{2}}{\frac{k^{2}}{\left(1-k^{2}\right)}}=c^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an elliptical cone (equation of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{y^{2}}{b^{2}}=z^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=\frac{k}{\sqrt{\left(1-k^{2}\right)}}$
\end_inset

).
 Note that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in this range, the level set is a different elliptical cone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 we need 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0$
\end_inset

 for the nominator and the denominator to equal.
 So all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}=\left(a,b,0\right)$
\end_inset

 would solve the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\vec{u}\right)=k=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $k>1$
\end_inset

 there are no solutions since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{b^{2}+a^{2}}\leq\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
